A Veolia forklift operator was moving a cubic yard box out of the back of a parked trailer. The operator misjudged the distance to the IBC behind the cubic yard box and the left fork of the truck punctured the tote. The tote discharged its contents into the trailer which leaked onto the driveway of Veolia's 10 day intransit facility. The operator immediately applied absorbent material to the spill inside the trailer and on the driveway. The spill was contained and did not reach a drain or waterway.
column169: The forklift operator will receive refresher training and will have to pass a written and practical forklift test before he is able to operate the equipment again.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: On 11/4/2020 there was an odor from a plastic carboy (051H1) when the carboy was at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY transportation terminal. Upon inspection it was determined that there was a small crack in the plastic carboy at the top of the container. The carboy was placed in a 30 Gallon fiber drum with a bag and spill pads in it. The bag was not sealed. During handling and transport, the container may have been further compromised while using a forklift to load the containers onto an outgoing vehicle on 11/5/2020.  Upon arrival at the destination location in Middlesex, NJ on 11/5/2020, the fiber drum was visibly wet with liquid and had a bad odor. No free liquids were observed in the vehicle. It is estimated that a small amount of less than a pint of liquid leaked out of the crack of the carboy and into the 30 gallon fiber drum and was absorbed by the cardboard of the drum. The fiber drum was further over-packed into a plastic drum at the Veolia, Middlesex, NJ destination location to prevent it from leaking.  On 11/6/2020 the Veolia safety manager investigated what occurred at the Schenectady, NY transportation terminal. It was discovered that employees who were told originally about the crack in the 5 gallon carboy had discussed what they thought was the best way to overpack the leaking carboy. Instead of using an appropriate plastic overpack container, they decided to use a fiber drum and use a plastic bag and some spill pads to try and assure that the 5-gallon carboy would not leak.
column169: As part of the followup investigation on 11/6/20, it was determined that the manager of the Veolia, Schenectady, NY facility will be notified of any leaking containers in the future and will review with employees the best method to overpack a leaking container or to prevent any further leaking of containers. This will be a new standard operating procedure at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY location.  Additionally all Veolia employees in the New England district will be trained on spill prevention and review the incident that occurred.  In the future, any containers of liquid that appear to be leaking will be prohibited from being packaged in a fiber container.

column168: The tank car was reported leaking by Mechanical Manager while the car was on the RIP track in Livonia, LA. Responder stopped the release by tightening the loose bottom outlet valve cap on the car. The bottom outlet valve will not close completely and the shipper is requesting an OTMA to move the car to a tank car shop for repair.

The tank car was reported leaking by UPRR yard personnel. Responder arrived on scene and discovered some residue product near the man way on top of the car. The man way gasket was checked and determined to be the source of the release. The gasket was replaced and the man way secured properly.

Car was found to be releasing vapor and from the ground appeared to be the rupture disc assembly.  Upon inspection it was confirmed that the rupture disc was blown and was replaced with a compatible rupture disc.  The release was stopped at that time.  The car was monitored for approximately 30 min with no vapor present.  The pressure plate was neutralized and the car was released back into transportation.
column169: Ensure car is ready for transport prior to releasing

On 11/10/2020, at 1445, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered PROX 74595, a loaded tank car of Waste Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid N.O.S. (Lead), leaking from manway cover. The car was isolated and GFL Environmental, NRC, and IDEM were notified. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an unsecure manway cover with 6 of 6 manway bolts less then tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Jason Henkel, 204-781-2600. Contractor personnel secured the manway cover and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.   Cause Code: 200 NARRI: 5
column169: (NAR Cause Code 200 5 What Failed: Manway, Hinged & Bolted Where Failed: Connection between manway nozzle and manway cover Why Failed: Bolts/nuts - less than tool tight)

column168: RESPONDED TO A PACKAGE THAT NEEDED TO BE REWRAPPED. UPON INSPECTION OF CONTENTS DISCOVERED UNDECLARED AMMUNITION. AMMO FIRE ACCESS HORNADY 6.5 GRENDEL 123GR ELD MATCH BLACK. NO HAZMAT MARKS OR LABELS ON OUTER CARTON. THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.
A DECLARED HAZMAT WAS FOUND LEAKING AT DESTINATION. THE CONTENTS WERE LEAKING FROM THE PRODUCT CLOSURE.

After finishing the loading process, driver got distracted while sitting in the truck.  He drove off without disconnecting hose, shutting valves, etc. Driver stated that he got to county blacktop (approximately 250 yards away) and realized he was losing air to trailer.  He stopped to check it out and realized oil was coming out of trailer.  Driver shut his internals and called his terminal manager. He drove back on location immediately awaiting assistance.  Local fire department responded and deployed booms to assist in containment.  Sentinel Safety contacted CURA Emergency Services who agreed to utilize the on-site local response crew already at the scene to continue to manage the incident.  Environmental contractor at the scene dispatched vacuum truck, absorbent, booms, and remediated the area. Local and state regulatory and reporting agencies were contacted including Chemtrec, OK DEP, OK Corporation Commission, and local Fire Department.

At 14:37ET, LandStar called to report a 50-pound release of UN3077 "VULKACIT NZ/EG-C"  from (1) 1,150-pound super sack impacting the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to clean the release. The contractor arrived and reported that there was no dunnage or load securement inside the trailer. The product shifted off the pallet tearing the super sack. The contractor transferred the product into 2 replacement supersacks. The contractor utilized a vacuum to collect the released product. All waste was collected and taken off site for pending disposal.

When loading freight into trailer, forklift operator struck a drum with the forkblades of the forklift consequently puncturing it and contribution to the unintentional release. Drum was immediately laid on its side and spilled material was cleaned with absorbent material. Drum was repaired with drum putty and placed into a recovery container as was the absorbents used to clean and mitigate the unintentionally released material.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: On November 09, 2020 at 11:40 hours, personnel in the CSXT Brunswick yard reported an odor from car WCHX 23123, a residue tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine.  The car was isolated and the shipper, IFF Chemical Holdings, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2020-1109-00139.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor release from the car’s manway cover.  The manway cover was not properly aligned due to an out of adjustment safety collar on one of the cover’s bolts.   Additionally, MEI noted damage to the suspect cover bolt’s safety collar that appeared to be due to tightening the manway cover nut with the safety collar out of adjustment.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative: Luke Moore (706-799-7885).  Contractor personnel adjusted the safety collar and secured the manway cover to stop the vapor release. The car was held at the CSX Brunswick, MD yard pending receipt of a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA for movement to home shop for repair of the defective manway cover bolt/safety collar.

Switch crew on duty at Calvert heard hissing from RACX51449.  Car showed to be residue last contained Flammable Liquid from Cymetech, a customer in the Calvert Complex where the car was heard hissing.  Notifications, including to Cymetech, were made.  Paul Petitt from Cymetech responded and advised the car was a residue but empty of product.  The car had been put under slight pressure with nitrogen to prevent a vacuum in transit.  Mr. Petitt advised no product was leaking because the product had a very low odor threshold of 8 ppm and was not able to be smelled.  The manway was found to be tight, but was tightened more.  The car was then transferred into their facility in the complex for repair of the manway gasket.  Mr. Petitt stated the gasket was crushed as if it had been overtightened in the past, but was not actually physically into or pinched.

column168: On 11/6/2020 appoximately 2 L of sodium hydroxide solution was released from a container that was not UN rated while in transit. Veolia employees were outside of the vehicle on a break when they noticed about 100 ml of the sodium hydroxide solution on the ground in a store parking lot in Franklin, MA. Once the Veolia employees noticed the spill outside of the vehicle they went into the back of the vehicle to investigate. The container that was leaking was a 40 gallon open-top poly drum with a poly bladder inside. At the bottom of the container has an opening where the bladder hose would normally come through. The hose on the bladder was clamped and the bottom opening and lid were taped. These containers have been shipped in the past but they contained non-DOT regulated material. The Veolia employees cleaned up the spill and over-packed the container to prevent further release.   The release of material most likely came from a small hole in the inner bladder. The Veolia employees could tell that the hose was not leaking. The material that leaked from the bladder then came out through the opening at the bottom of the poly drum. Hazardous materials should not have been shipped in this type of container because it was not rated to do so. Before accepting for transportation the sodium hydroxide solution should have been transferred into the proper UN specification package or overpacked into a container that had the proper UN rating. The Veolia employees who accepted this container for transportation are knowledgeable of the requirements for transporting hazardous materials.
column169: To prevent this from occurring again, this incident will be shared with all districts throughout Veolia, at a nationwide level. There will also be training at the local office that shipped the container that discusses the importance of verifying containers are compatible and proper for transportation of hazardous materials.

column168: On November 17, 2020 at 07:36 hours personnel at the CSX Curtis Bay Yard in Baltimore, MD noticed an odor in the area of UTLX 950466, a residue tank car of liquefied petroleum gas.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Thompson Gas Propane Holdings, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2020-1117-00067).  HEPACO, a CSX response contractor, was dispatched to investigate the source of the odor and found the tank car’s vapor line valve was not fully closed and the vapor line valve’s secondary closure plug was not properly secured.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Lynn Paquette 413-386-7019).  The vapor line valve was closed and the secondary securement plug installed wrench tight.  The car was released for transportation.

column168: Owner operator for AmeriGas PTI had a rollover incident on 49 Street in Evans, CO.  The transport was en-route to Commerce City, CO.  The right front steer tire went off the shoulder of the road and the driver attempted to steer back onto the pavement.   The incident occurred when the driver attempted to reach down for something on the floor behind causing him to take his eyes of the road.  He drove onto the shoulder of the road.   There were no leaks.  Wrecker called to up upright the transport The transport was off-loaded onto another unit. Emergency services were called to the scene and responded.
column169: The incident was the result of driver being distracted while driving.  AmeriGas PTI conducted a safety stand down call with all transport drivers, managers and supervisors.  Communicated the rollover and discussed distracted driving

THE HAZ-MAT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING ON THE FLOOR OF PD-7 DOCK, IN THE EARTH CITY, MO UPS HUB AT 19:00 HOURS. THE PACKAGE (A DOUBLE WALLED, 12X12X12IN, 51LBS EDGE CRUSH TEST, FIBERBOARD BOX) WAS FOUND ON ITS SIDE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED, CONTAINED, AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. AN EXTERNAL INSPECTION REVEALED NO SIGNS OF ABUSE FROM THE SHIPPING PROCESS. AN INTERNAL INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS NO PACKING MATERIAL BETWEEN THE INNER RECEPTACLES (1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES), OR BETWEEN THEM AND THE CARTON WALL. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILLAGE WAS A LOOSE CAP COMBINED WITH THE PACKAGE BEING ON ITS SIDE. ALL MATERIAL HAS BEEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.

A contractor was dispatched and containerized the damaged container and cleaned up the minimal release. All waste was staged on site pending shipper instructions on disposal activities.

column168: On November 11, 2020 at 10:30 Mechanical personnel in the Conrail Port Reading Yard discovered , TAEX 30187 a residue  tank car of Hydrocarbons, Liquid (natural gasoline)  leaking from the bottom outlet valve area of the tank car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Kinder Morgan was notified directly via phone . Conrail Manager of  Hazardous Material, Joe Caccamo along with Marion Environmental personnel, investigated the leak and found  the source to appear to be above the valve at the flange of the tank car. The leak was unable to be stopped so  a spill containment pan was placed beneath the valve to catch the dripping product. The tank car was then  placed on the wye track where it could be further inspected and made safe. Adam Kelly, Operations Supervisor  for Kinder Morgan 267-885-5481 arrived to inspect the tank car. It was decided that the safest course of action would be to  clean and purge the tank car and obtain One Time Movement Approval for home shop repairs. The tank car was  clean and purged, placards were removed, the faulty valve was tagged, and the tank car was labeled for home  shop repair "do not load". It is awaiting final waybill updates to be placed back into transportation to home shop.   Cause Code: 147 5 x ( 4 + 5 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 0 ) = 90

column168: On November 8 2020 at 21:00 hrs EST CN's Dangerous Goods Officer was contacted by CN Transportation Supervisor, Battle Creek, MI reporting that the crew switching car ASOX299057 track SB14 had reported an odor. All appropriate departments notified and tank car isolated. CN's response team responded and found that car ASOX299057, load, UN2049, DIETHYLBENZENE, Class 3, PG III was leaking vapor from the vacuum relief valve area. The VRV was removed, finding that the O-Ring in the VRV was both swelled and dislodged from its seat. The VRV was replaced with 2.5# plug, car then pressured up to 10psi using nitrogen, and bubble checked the car held the pressure for 15 minutes.

column168: On 11/3/2020 at 1751 ET, Landstar tractor truck #426469 and trailer #826469 were involved in a single - vehicle roll over accident at the above referenced location. As a result, approximately 3,000 gallons of UN3264, Corrosive liquid, acidic, inorganic, nos, 8, PGIII "Phosphorous Acid" released impacting the asphalt roadway and soil alongside the roadway. No drains or waterways were reported impacted by this release. Haz Mat Special Services LLC out of San Antonio, TX was dispatched to perform emergency response and cleanup operations. At 2215 ET, Haz Mat Special Services LLC personnel arrived onsite and reported that approximately 3,000 gallons of UN3264, Corrosive liquid, acidic, inorganic, nos, 8, PGIII "Phosphorous Acid" had released from (13) 275 - gallon poly totes impacting all four lanes of the highway stretching out 150 yards as well as a 30' by 80' area of soil alongside the highway. The contractor began performing tote transfers to recover the product remaining in the totes. Three (3) new 275 - gallon totes were filled with the remaining product in the 13 totes, approximately 600 gallons total. The damaged totes were placed into one (1) roll off box to be transported offsite. Granular absorbents and neutralizer were applied to the impacted area of the asphalt roadway to absorb, solidify and neutralize the free - standing product. Haz Mat Special Services LLC personnel collected the spent absorbents into one (1) additional roll off box which was transported offsite. The impacted area of soil was secured with poly sheeting until further remediation could be coordinated. On 11/12/2020, Haz Mat Special Services LLC personnel returned to the site and applied a sodium bicarbonate solution to the area of impacted soil and gravel. pH tests were conducted confirming neutrality. Six confirmation samples were collected before personnel departed the site. Disposal of the waste generated is still pending at this time.

Driver was traveling approximately 40 mph in a 45 mph zone and had a sneezing fit.  Right passenger tires left pavement onto soft embankment (no shoulder) into a ditch.  The truck traveled approximately 100 yards traversing a culvert which broke the hose reel and piping on the rear deck of the truck.  The truck ended up on its right side.  The driver made sure that the the belly valve was closed and moved away from the vehicle.  Vapor from the broken piping was released into the atmosphere.  Super Flame Gas personnel (along with volunteer Fire Dept. personnel) approached truck and closed a valve on the rear end of the truck to stop the leak.  We estimate that only 5 gallons of propane was lost.  There was no fire.
column169: We discussed the accident with the driver.  All drivers had been trained on Rollover Prevention this past summer.  All driver and task specific training is up to date and documented.

column168: A HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS KNOCKED OFF THE IRREG BELT NEAR DOOR 201 IN THE BLUE AREA. IT FELL APPROXIMATELY 2 FEET HIT THE FLOOR. IT IMMEDIATELY STARTED LEAKING. THE IRREG SORTER NEXT TO IT NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR   THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I PUT SODIUM BICARBONATE ON THE LIQUID TO NEUTRALIZE IT. I THEN SOLIDIFIED ALL REMAINING LIQUID WITH CLAY ABSORBENT. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS   PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT ONE OF THE CAPS WAS BROKEN   THAT THE 3 REMAINING BOTTLES WERE SOILED BY THE PRODUCT.

column168: When the driver went  to offload he hooked up his special fitting to the trailer and his hose to the fitting and shimmed the camlock connections as they felt a little loose.  When he began to open his valves product began leaking out of where the fitting is attached to the trailer.  Most went in to a catch bucket and 16 oz's hit the asphalt.  Customer handled the clean up.
column169: When the driver went to unload he hooked up a special fitting we have for these trailers.  The special fitting incorporates a bleeder valve in to it so we can clear the lines if need me in the middle of delivery.  This fitting sticks out a bit more than a standard fitting.  On the original model containers like this that we bought some had come with an external discharge valve fitting that was machined slightly different.  With the weight of a hose hanging off this extended fitting it would pull down on the gasket enough to create a gap and allow product to leak out.  The fix was to use slightly thicker gaskets and were issued and utilized when making these deliveries.  This driver did not have one.  He took the special fitting out and used a regular reducer fitting which worked just fine to finish the offload.  We are now working on a plan to get a report of those trailers that have had a fitting replaced over the years and any that haven't will be replaced as they are routed in for any maintenence.  This will eliminate the need to try and ensure the drivers have this thicker gasket and not having it when the need arises.

Driver reportedly coughed to clear throat. The cough was so hard that for a short period they couldn't see road and felt the vehicle drifting. Driver over corrected and rolled the vehicle. Ended upside down, driver felt for seatbelt and dropped down. Pain in right pec and neck. A witness called for emergency responders.   The 1000gal cargo tank separated from the vehicle during the roll over. Pressure change resulted in the laden product rapidly flashing into dry ice with trace vapors escaping from the exposed piping/ports. Fire department applied a wet patch over the tank leaving at least 1 port able to depressurize the vessel. Sealing the cargo tank from venting would create a greater potential of danger. The dry ice slowly continued to exhaust from the tank within possession of the remediation group that recovered and stored it - duration unknown. Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality (DEQ) representative arrived on scene to assess - no dangers or adverse environmental effects, and ensured fuel spill was arranged.  Driver was coherent with emergency responders and taken to the hospital as a direct result of the vehicle roll. Fire department used the emergency response hotline from the driver's manifest. Company operations and safety officials coordinated with all emergency responders, remediation, state environmental. The tank and vehicle were cleared from the scene. PD Officer confirmed that the road closures were NOT due to the hazardous materials, rather the vehicle and tank blocking traffic. The driver was verified to be current in their DOT physical and hours of service limitations at the time of incident.  Note: Fuel clean-up costs are combined into response total in this report based on the environmental services company invoice.

On 11/3/2020, at approximately 9:00 a.m DG Admin received a report of a sealed lead-acid, non-spillable battery emitting a dangerous evolution of heat during sort. Per the specialist, the package began to release sparks cause unknown. The Spill Clean-up team was called. Upon arriving, the specialist conducted an inspection of the battery itself and discovered that the terminals on the battery were exposed and had displayed evidence of charring. The terminals themselves also appeared to have melted. While the outer packaging appeared to be prepared under IATA Special Provision A67, but does not comply the special provision fully, as the terminals did not appear to be protected. The shipper was notified and authorized disposal of the battery.

On November 4,2020, personnel at the R+L Carriers(RLC) terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a cargo leak in trailer OA3881. Upon further inspection, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3266 potassium hydroxide leaked approximately one(1) cup of product from the drum's cap to the interior of the trailer. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LLC(ER) to perform the necessary corrective action. Crew members replaced the cap on the drum to prevent further Ieakage. ER deployed absorbents and neutralizing solution to the impacted surfaces. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one(1) 5-gallon bucket for transport and disposal. Crews secured the scene and demobilized.

On 11/19/2020 at 1359hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Avon IN Terminal discovered HBLU320231, a loaded container of residue UN1197, Extracts Flavorings, Class 3, PG III, in baled empty crushed plastic containers for recycle; released less than 2gals of liquid form rear of container onto asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and notified to NRC (report#1292617) and IDEM (report#94237).  The shipper, Hapag-Lloyd (630-328-1497), representative was notified by CSXI Customer Service, cris file#379360.  CSXT emergency response contractor, HEPACO Environmental, was dispatched to the scene and found several bales of recycled plastics releasing liquid (about 15gals inside container and 2gals outside onto asphalt). Release due to bales of recycle plastics loaded, stacked, and pressed allowing residual liquids to accumulate. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the release by transfer of lading from intermodal shipping container HBLU320231 into HBLU318336; deconned spilled areas; and cleaned up the release site.   HBLU320231…the original freight container, now empty, is also reported to be an Undeclared HazMat shipment.  The shipper could not provide certification of clean & purge for the bales of recycle plastics.  The bales retained the DOT Labels for UN1197.  HBLU318336…the freight container the lading was transferred into, was billed as a HazMat shipment per the shipper provided SDS:  UN1197, Extract Flavorings, 3, III.  This incident did not require a special switching move. This incident did not require a Form 7.1.  Report is being filed late due to the shipper insisting that the shipment was non-hazardous but could not provide the proper documentation that the crushed containers that they were cleaned and purged of residue product

column168: A dangerous goods package or UN1263 Paint, Packing Group 11 was observed leaking during PM sort operations at the origin ramp, GSPR, in Greer, SC. The outer packaging had a wet corner and was emitting an odor. The involved package, tracking number 935316646027, was part of a 28 piece shipment but was the only package in the shipment that was observed with a leak. The outer fiberboard box contained three inner metal 1 gallon cans. A small amount leaked from the closure of one of the inner containers into the outer packaging, which dampened the box. The product in the leaking can was Hentzen Coatings RED 913 GF1 Wood Additive Solvent/Reducer. The outer box did have dangerous goods markings and labeling, and a Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The ramp was initially directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further. disposition instruction. The shipper subsequently picked up the shipment.

column168: A FedEx padded pak was observed leaking at the destination FedEx Express station in Philadelphia, PA. The pak was associated with tracking number 771991005529, and was the master package in a multiple piece shipment with three pieces. It was the only one observed leaking. Investigation showed that the package contained two plastic 8 oz bottles of Purell Advanced Hand Sanitizer and one 19 oz aerosol can of Lysol Disinfectant spray. The cap of the spray bottle of Lysol broke, allowing the leak and the entire contents spilled. The hand sanitizer is labeled as 70 percent ethyl alcohol, but it was shipped in a quantity that meets exceptions to the HMR as listed in 49CFR173.150G. However, the Lysol Disinfectant Spray is classified as Class 2.1 dangerous goods, specifically UN1950, Aerosols, Flammable per the SDS document associated with the product. There were no dangerous goods markings or labels on the package observed by operations staff at the time of discovery and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

column169: The first preventative measure for this particular accident is better route planning. Going forward this route will not be approved for our drivers. After the accident we were informed by the SCHP that this particular road was not CMV friendly and that they continue to have numerous CMV accidents as result. More in depth training is also needed to better enforce our existing policy, to include defensive driving, rollover prevention and avoiding' distracted/drowsy driving. With these measures our drivers will be better trained to handle certain driving conditions and will be able to understand what to do to minimize/reduce the possibilities of serious crashes.

column25: BIG RIVER RESOURCES WEST BURLINGTON, LLC
column168: Driver was driving a semi tractor pulling a tank trailer heading southbound on US-67.  The driver went off the right side of the road , over corrected and then lost control of the tractor trailer .  The tractor trailer overturned coming to rest on the passenger side in the southbound ditch. Emergency personnel were notified immediately after the incident. The tank trailer was breached due to the impact of the rollover.  Responders diked the area to prevent further contamination.  SET Environmental was dispatched  to the scene for cleanup.
column169: After accident investigation , review of video and speed reports, it was determined that the driver was speeding over 10 mph (66 in a 55) over the speed limit the driver and was distracted by something he was reaching for between the seats. It was also observed that the driver had his cell phone sitting in his lap and it was lit up as if in use.  The truck went off the side of the road and the driver was unable to regain control. It had been raining for several days prior to the incident and the shoulder was soft.  Company initiatives going forward : Working closely with our insurance company, Great West Casualty, on accident mitigation, implementing  new orientation policies and procedures and utilizing the telematics tools for hard brake, speed and hard curve events that have recently become available to us through our ELD provider, KeepTruckin.  We will also be putting together a journey Management Plan for these routes focusing on hazards and dangers enroute.  There is a company wide push on speeding and distracted driving prevention through one-on -one intervention, flyers and video training through the driver tablets.
